
    ---
    Base Spells (Tips)

    These define how you hit, not how hard:

    - Single — one cell, reliable
    - Line — column or row, punishes clustering
    - Arc — hits cells adjacent to target (flanking feel)
    - Lob — hits a cell 2 away, skips adjacent (bypasses front line)
    - Cross — target + 4 cardinal neighbors
    - Ricochet — hits target, then bounces to a random adjacent enemy

    ---
    Body Spells (Modifiers — interesting design space)

    The goal is spells that change what happens, not just how much:

    Elemental reactions
    - Ignite — target burns for 2 damage next turn (delayed, stacks with other sources)
    - Chill — frozen target skips its next action
    - Poison — damage over time, scales with stacks

    Wand shape modifiers
    - Amplify — doubles damage of the next body spell in the chain
    - Split — fires the tip twice at two different targets
    - Recoil — big damage boost, but damages the mage slightly

    Utility / positioning
    - Push — knocks the target back one cell
    - Pull — drags target toward your party
    - Swap — exchanges positions of two enemies

    Conditional
    - Execute — deals bonus damage to enemies below 30% HP
    - Overkill — excess damage spills to adjacent enemies
    - Resonance — deals extra damage if the same element was used last turn

    Resource manipulation
    - Drain — converts enemy HP into global mana
    - Overcharge — spend 2 extra mana for a massive damage spike this zap only
    - Echo — repeats the last zap at half power for free

    ---
    Design Principles Worth Keeping

    - Reactions over raw power: a Chill + Shatter combo (freeze then deal bonus damage) is more satisfying than +5 damage
    - Positioning matters: Push/Pull/Swap make the enemy grid feel tactical rather than decorative
    - Wand synergy: spells that care about other spells in the same wand create build decisions — you're crafting a machine, not just picking big numbers
    - Downside spells: Recoil, Overcharge — risk/reward creates tension
    - Information asymmetry: DoT and delayed effects make turns feel consequential beyond the immediate hit
